<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on CIS Leaders Summit 15 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on CIS Leaders Summit 15 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kazakh Premier Predicts Support for Union </H4>

<F P=102> LD1504173994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1521 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and 
others] 
  [Text] The former Soviet republics will not be capable of 
overcoming the situation they are in separately. The way out 
provides for support of the initiative on establishment of a 
Eurasian union put forward by Kazakh President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev. This was suggested by Kazakh Foreign Minister 
Tuleutay Suleymenov in an interview with Interfax. 
  Suleymenov clarified that the Kazakh president's proposal 
meant that the economy must finally prevail over the politics. 
"The CIS in its present framework does not work. Its documents 
(there are already more than 400 of them adopted) are not 
carried out. If two, three or four states interested in a close 
cooperation join the Eurasian union, it will work," Suleymenov 
suggested. 
  He said many people were worrying that establishment of 
over-national organizational structures might violate the 
sovereignty. "However, Kazakhstan is not afraid of this. That 
is why President Nazarbayev has put forward this initiative," he 
added. 
  Suleymenov is certain that the CIS states will back the 
Kazakh initiative in the near future "some earlier, some later." 
"Definite mechanisms of interaction do exist. There is no use 
to reinvent the wheel. For instance, there is the European 
Union [EU] is it not an example which should be followed? This 
is a single customs and economic space with inter-state banks 
and mutual settlement. By the way, the sharp issue on dual 
citizenship would be resolved." One would be able to change the 
citizenship freely, Suleymenov stressed. 
  Suleymenov believes that there is no reasonable alternative 
to the Eurasian union. "We need each other. Even now our 
former Soviet republics are more integrated with each other than 
the EU states. We must unite. We have separated in order to 
reunite on a new basis," Suleymenov suggested. 
  On the convention on human rights for ethnic minorities 
submitted for additional work on it, Suleymenov emphasized its 
importance and necessity for Kazakhstan. 
  "The draft convention was considered by the Council of 
Foreign Ministers for the third time already. We have 
repeatedly put forward our proposals and recommendations. 
Unfortunately, experts do not always take into consideration 
the recommendations of all the CIS states. That is why 
documents turn out to be incomplete. This happened once again," 
Suleymenov said. 
  He announced that the CIS foreign ministers had agreed to 
reconsider the convention in mid-May in order to discuss it once 
again and to submit it for approval by the heads of state. "We 
would like this document to work in favor not only of Kazakhstan 
but also in favor of the whole CIS. It concerns our burning 
issues. That is why the convention must be brought to conformity 
with the national legislation of all the CIS states," Suleymenov 
pointed out. 
  He stressed that Kazakhstan was also very interested in 
another document - the declaration on sovereignty, territorial 
integrity and inviolability of the CIS states' borders. "These 
issues are of great importance for us now. We are satisfied 
with the adoption of this document," Suleymenov stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

