<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on CIS Leaders Summit 15 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on CIS Leaders Summit 15 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kyrgyz President Views Summit </H4>

<F P=102> LD1504214194 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1800 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504214194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] CIS heads of state signed a final package of 
documents at their meeting in Moscow today. Its basis is a bloc 
of economic agreements: on Ukraine's joining the economic union 
as an associate member; on creating an economic union 
commission; and on forming a free trade zone. In addition, a 
declaration was approved on the observance of sovereignty, 
territorial integrity, and the inviolability of Commonwealth 
borders. 
  In an interview with our correspondent, President of 
Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan] Askar Akayev expressed satisfaction with 
today's meeting between heads of state. In his view, the 
meeting fulfilled its main task. 
  [Begin Akayev recording] First, it is the creation of a 
permanently functioning committee. Or rather, the heads of 
government introduced such an amendment--an economic commission 
that will be located in Moscow and will monitor the 
implementation of adopted agreements on trade and economic 
cooperation. CIS bodies are at last appearing that could 
develop in the future into an effective mechanism for 
implementing agreements. [end recording] 
  Despite the fact that Kazakh President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev's 
proposal to set up a Eurasian union was not examined today, 
Akayev said that he wholly supports this idea. 
  [Begin Akayev recording] I see it as the foreseeable future 
of our CIS. If the mechanisms for cooperation laid down by the 
CIS are implemented to a significant extent, we will arrive at a 
Eurasian union. [end recording] 
  For his part, Boris Yeltsin made special note of the 
agreement signed in Moscow today on extending the term for CIS 
peacekeeping forces in Tajikistan, and also the joint statements 
on the situation in Abkhazia and Nagornyy Karabakh 
[Nagorno-Karabakh]. The next session of heads of state will 
take place on 9 September. 

</TEXT>

