<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cites NATO `Trap', Serb `Victims' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cites NATO `Trap', Serb `Victims' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504141194 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1200 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A news conference by the leader of the Liberal 
Democratic Party faction was held on the results of the Council 
of Europe session, at which Vladimir Zhirinovskiy sharply 
opposed the possible signing by Russia of NATO's Partnership for 
Peace program. 
  [Begin Zhirinovskiy recording] I am glad that our country's 
political leadership has made a correct step in this regard. 
For the first time in the four months since the State Duma' 
started working, we can react positively to President Yeltsin's 
steps on his refusal to go to Brussels to sign the document 
which is called the Partnership for Peace program. Lovely words 
-- Partnership for Peace -- anyone would think, but in fact it 
is an ideological trap. The more paper we sign, the more 
European and international structures we climb aboard, the more 
we will be taken by the throat and forced to implement documents 
they create. [end recording] 
  [Kuznetsova] There was a short silence and then Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy tackled the Serbian question. 
  [Begin Zhirinovskiy recording] I am fully on the side of the 
Serbs. The Serbs are victims of aggression. What is happening 
in the Balkans today is a scenario for the gradual annihilation 
of Russia. The Americans are (?trying it out) on a small 
region. Just like the Russians in Russia -- the former USSR -- 
so it is with the Serbs in Yugoslavia. [end recording] 
  [Kuznetsova] A statement was made that henceforth the party 
will use the title Zhirinovskiy's Party, since Boris Fedorov, 
the leader of a new political formation, called it the Liberal 
Democratic Union of 12 December. 

</TEXT>

