<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Strasbourg Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Strasbourg Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504202294 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] In the break between budget discussions, the LDPR 
[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia] leader decided to tell the 
media about his visit to Strasbourg as part of the Russian 
parliamentary delegation. In [Vladimir] Zhirinovskiy's words, 
it was difficult to work there because the French authorities 
limited his itinerary to three points: Charles de Gaulle 
airport, Strasbourg airport, and the city of Strasbourg. 
  [Begin Zhirinovskiy recording] They could have just shown me 
the toilet and told me where to piss, and where I should eat, 
and where I should sleep. That is all that remained to be 
shown. Otherwise, I might use the wrong toilet. [end recording] 
  Another example of Western inhospitality was the fact that 
the French do not speak Russian, which Zhirinovskiy considers 
essential even a long way from Russia. 
  [Begin Zhirinovskiy recording] It is only us Russians that 
mostly have to talk to them in their own languages. I spoke 
French, but I preferred to talk to them in Russian. All the 
more so because you cannot swear in another language. When they 
really made me angry, I found it easier to speak Russian, 
because you just cannot say it in French -- especially when 
those Jews attacked me at the consulate. Well, what can you say 
in French? All the words are so soft and nice. [end recording] 
  Zhirinovskiy said at the news conference that Russia should 
under no circumstances join the Council of Europe, which wants 
to make war on us using our own money. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

