<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leaders on Draft Civil Accord Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Leaders on Draft Civil Accord Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1504131794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 15 Apr 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1504131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yevgeniy Skukin account of interviews with Vasiliy </F>
Lipitskiy, chairman of the People's Party of Free Russia; 
Vladimir Lysenko, cochairman of the Republican Party of the 
Russian Federation; and Viktor Ilyukhin, representative of State 
Duma communist faction; place and date not given: "We Are 
Discussing the Draft Agreement on Civil Accord"] 
  [Text] Stabilization Means a Change of Policy 
  Vasiliy Lipitskiy, State Duma deputy and chairman of the 
People's Party of Free Russia: The worrying thing about this 
voluminous document is that, despite the general nature of its 
wording, it contains harsh sanctions for violations, the 
majority of which can be interpreted liberally, like, for 
example, "destabilizing the situation within society." 
  At the same time the agreement allows the application of 
sanctions up to and including the dismissal and removal of a 
deputy from his seat. I consider that the agreement may become 
a cause for limiting political freedom, and this cannot be 
allowed. 
  One more point. In order to achieve accord there should be 
policy changes. 
<H5>  Agreements Must Be Implemented </H5>
  Vladimir Lysenko, State Duma deputy, chairman of the 
subcommittee for developing federal relations, and cochairman of 
the Republican Party of the Russian Federation: The way I 
regard the draft is complex, as the president has already signed 
various documents of this type on many occasions, but not one of 
them has played a significant role as they were subsequently 
violated. What is more they were not violated by political 
forces but by the president. For example, an agreement was 
concluded with 15 parties in 1991 which subsequently faded into 
oblivion. So you cannot really rely on the agreement being 
equal at the moment. But the draft does contain positive 
elements. For example, with regard to a moratorium on changing 
a Federation component's status and the borders between 
Federation components. 
<H5>  We Are Ready To Present Our Own Solutions </H5>
  Viktor Ilyukhin, chairman of the State Duma Security 
Committee and representative of the communist faction: An 
accord is possible if several of our demands are met. First, if 
there is a change in the direction of the Russian reforms. It 
is not possible to reconcile oneself to the masses becoming 
impoverished. As the government is not putting forward any ways 
of extricating ourselves from the crisis, we will present our 
own solutions. 
  Second, the team which has brought the country to collapse 
has still not been changed to this day. 
  Third, we consider that the authorities should undertake 
never to use the Army for punitive purposes against the people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

