<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin Warns on `Dangerous' Media Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poltoranin Warns on `Dangerous' Media Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504170694 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1300 GMT 
15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mikhail Poltoranin, chairman of the State Duma 
Committee for Information Policy, told a RIA correspondent today 
that the single information area was in danger of 
disintegrating. He said that a dangerous policy--characterized 
by a trend toward replacing the state media with commercial 
structures interested in having their programs broadcast to 
central Russia only--could be discerned in the country. 
  The possibility that the Ostankino company might cut its 
output from 19 to five and a half hours in every 24 hours gave 
rise to particular anxiety in this context, Poltoranin noted. 
He emphasized that the activities of foreign news agencies in 
Russia also did tremendous damage to the country's sovereignty 
in the area of information. He said that having received the 
right to gather information, these agencies immediately 
disseminated it in the form they found convenient. This trend 
also posed dangers to the Russian information area, said the 
chairman of the information policy committee. 

</TEXT>

