<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Chief: Troops Can Be Used To Fight Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Chief: Troops Can Be Used To Fight Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504154394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1350 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In a letter to St. Petersburg's Mayor Anatoliy 
Sobchak Secretary Oleg Lobov of the Russian Security Council 
said the Russian military doctrine allowed the use of army units 
against organized crime if a region of the Russian Federation 
came under threat. The letter answers Sobchak's request for 
additional powers in the fight against crime. But, Lobov said, 
the Ministry of Internal Affairs must authorize the use of 
troops under its control. 
  According to Lobov, President Yeltsin was working on a 
decree 
on immediate moves for the protection of the citizens' 
constitutional rights and freedoms from criminal attacks. The 
decree would lay a legal foundation for the use of army units in 
anti-mafia operations and in a bid to maintain law and order. 
Bodies of the executive branch would enjoy the right to commit 
troops to action. 
  The decree would also grant the executive branch additional 
powers for controlling internal migration. Draft bills which 
introduce tougher penalties for unauthorized entry and stay in 
the Russian Federation, had been prepared and sent to the 
government. According to Lobov, the Mayor of St. Petersburg can, 
in his capacity as the chairman of the anti-crime and 
anti-corruption commission, coordinate moves by law and order 
bodies and plan long-term and immediate anti-crime actions in 
the region under his control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

