<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Addresses Petersburg EBRD Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Addresses Petersburg EBRD Session </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804102394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0912 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg April 18 TASS -- Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin today addressed the opening session 
of the board of directors of the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development [EBRD], which is holding its 
third annual meeting here today. 
  Viktor Chernomyrdin told the EBRD leaders and prominent 
statesmen and business people from the bank's fifty-seven 
stockholding countries that the forum in St. Petersburg is "a 
weighty testimony to the fact that the anxiety and uncertainty 
felt by our international partners about the fact of economic 
reforms in Russia, so pronounced at the beginning of the year, 
are now giving room to other sentiments and different 
expectations". 
  For his part, the Russian prime minister said "quite 
definitely and responsibly" that the policy of financial 
stabilisation, further reforms and restructuring of the national 
economy will remain the pivot of the Russian economic policy. 
Chernomyrdin pointed to the results of the first months of this 
year as bearing out his statement. In February and March, the 
inflation growth rate fell beneath ten per cent and the April 
figures will not differ considerably. The federal budget for the 
end of 1994 has been drafted with a deficit of about nine per 
cent of the gross product. It means that given the steady main 
parameters, the inflation growth rate will dwindle to seven per 
cent before the year is out. 
  The discussion of the draft budget in the Federal Assembly 
is 
proceeding with difficulties, Viktor Chernomyrdin stressed. The 
draft has been approved as the basis, and "we shall take into 
account any modifications approved by the deputies in line with 
the overall logic of the reforms carried out in Russia. 
  Political and financial stabilisation has already yielded 
its 
first fruit -- demand restrictions have begun to work. Although 
the production slump has been increasing since the beginning of 
the year, it has acquired a clear-cut structural character. 
  "We are now at the deepest point of the crisis," the prime 
minister said. The Russians have come quite close to the 
frontier beyond which U-turn can occur in the main negative 
tendencies which determined our development in the past 
two-three years. But the U-turn can occur only if investments 
liven up", Chernomyrdin said. The Russian premier appealed to 
the representatives of the European bank for reconstruction and 
development and the delegations from industrialised countries 
and international financial organisations to step up their 
activities on the Russian market. 
  Annual meetings of the board of directors of the EBRD 
traditionally examine the results of the bank's activity for the 
preceding year and determine guidelines for the next year. As 
concerns Russia, central bank officials told ITAR-TASS that the 
European bank has approved loans to fund 21 projects in Russia, 
including major ones, such as the development of the oilfield in 
the Arctic area of the Pechora basin, worth 300 million USD. By 
the end of this year, the number of approved projects, which are 
now being prepared, may reach fifty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16460 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov074_b_94027" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Predicts 7-8 Percent Inflation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Predicts 7-8 Percent Inflation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804082294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0729 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Igor Ignatyev and Sergey </F>
Oleynik] 
  [Text] St. Petersburg April 18 TASS -- Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin pledged adherence to market reforms 
and predicted that inflation may be curtailed to 7-8 per cent by 
the end of the year if the budget drafted for 1994 is approved 
by the State Duma. 
  "The course towards reforms, financial stabilisation and 
economic restructuring remains the backbone of the Russian 
economic policy", Chernomyrdin told a meeting of the governors 
of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development which 
opened in the second biggest Russian city on Monday. 
  He recalled that in the first quarter of 1994 inflation was 
below the 10 per cent level and predicted it would be further 
curtailed to monthly 7-8 per cent by the end of the year "if the 
planned parametres of the budget are preserved". The Russian 
State Duma gave an outline approval to the draft budget, but 
demanded that the government introduces certain corrections to 
it. 

</TEXT>

