<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Favors State Regulation, Protectionism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Favors State Regulation, Protectionism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804105994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1010 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Yelmakov] </F>
  [Text] Novosibirsk April 18 TASS -- Deputy Prime Minister 
Sergey Shakhray supported state regulation and protectionism in 
the regional policy, when he was speaking today at a scientific 
and practical conference in Novosibirsk. The purpose of the 
conference is to work out a strategy of stabilising the economic 
situation in the region. 
  The diversity of regions and the multinational character of 
the Russian state are not the source of its weakness, but, on 
the contrary, a factor of its potential might. At the same 
time, he pointed to the growing disproportion among regions and 
a trend towards economic disintegration. According to Shakhray, 
some regions are stepping up economic transformations, others 
are preserving old methods and approaches to the economic 
development. There is not a single region in Russia without 
problems today, he said. 
  Shakhray described as rather ineffective the market-oriented 
mechanisms of eliminating disproportions in the development of 
the regions. This is why, he continued, a tougher regional 
policy is needed, whose main task will be to bring to naught the 
contrasts between living standards of the population of various 
regions. 
  The conference is being attended by representatives of 25 
regions of Russia, of the Federation Council, the State Duma, 
many ministries and organisations, as well as by scientists. 

</TEXT>

