<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Ossetia Ready for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    N. Ossetia Ready for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604212194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2032 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1604212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz April 17 TASS -- "A way to accord 
between the peoples of North Ossetia and Ingushetia is hard, but 
we must move towards it," North Ossetia President Akhsarbek 
Galazov said. Addressing members of North Ossetia government 
and parliament leaders in Vladikavkaz on Saturday, Galazov spoke 
about the results of the second round of talks between the 
presidents and official delegations of North Ossetia and 
Ingushetia in Nalchik, capital of neighbouring Kabardino-Balkar 
Republic. 
  Galazov said the talks were difficult and centered on the 
draft agreement on the principles, measures and terms of the 
implementation of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's decree 
establishing the procedure for returning refugees and displaced 
persons to North Ossetia and Ingushetia. 
  Disagreements over who should control the disputed 
Prigorodny 
district were the "stumbling block" at the talks. North Ossetia 
claims the district is its integral part, while Ingushetia 
insists that the district belongs to it because it was inhabited 
by Ingushes before they were deported in 1944. 
  Galasov stressed that "the question of border redrawing in 
the northern Caucasus must be removed from the agenda because 
territorial claims may lead to a new tragedy in Russia's south." 
  The two republics will resume talks after April 25 when the 
Federation Council, the upper house of Russia's new parliament, 
holds debates on the situation in the region and ways to 
stabilise it. 
  The North Ossetian leader noted that the sides have reached 
"progress in normalising relations between the peoples of the 
two republics and dispelled pessimistic forecasts that the 
dialogue in Nalchik would end in a deadlock." "The leadership 
of North Ossetia is ready to carry out the decree of the Russian 
president," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16487 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov074_d_94010" </HT>


