<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Lessen Tensions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Lessen Tensions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704102494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1003 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704102494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz April 17 TASS--Russian troops loyal to 
the temporary administration have begun a large-scale operation, 
removing mines on the North Ossetian territory where a state of 
emergency remains in effect. Lieutenant-General Vladimir 
Kulakov, commander of the Vladikavkaz military garrison, told 
ITAR-TASS that field engineers have been instructed to draw a 
chart of mine fields within a week and check the safety of 
economic facilities, transport thoroughfares and gas pipelines. 
  Several incidents were reported in the Prigorodny region, 
where agricultural machinery and several agricultural workers 
exploded on mines planted by terrorists. Military sources say 
that the situation in North Ossetia where a state of emergency 
was extended until May 31, remains rather complex, but kept 
under control by Russian peace-keeping forces and local law 
enforcement bodies. 
  Local observers believe that a second round of talks held in 
Nalchik by North Ossetian President Akhsarbek Galazov and Ingush 
President Ruslan Aushev gave a certain impetus, helping to 
relieve tension in the Prigorodny region. 
  Local observers believe that a discussion of problems of 
stabilisation in the region expected to be held by the Russian 
Federation Council and the Russian Security Council in the 
context of the Russian president's decree on the return of 
refugees will help to disentangle a difficult knot of 
international problems. 
  Akhsarbek Galazov met with commander of a special Caucasian 
border guard district, Lieutenant-General Viktor Zemtsov, the 
press service of the North Ossetian president reported on 
Sunday. During the meeting the sides discussed a number of 
problems connected with reinforcing Russia's southern borders. 
The talks were attended by North and South Ossetian government 
officials who expressed concern about the fact that the 
introduction of the network of border-check points on the 
Transcaucasian road will remove a "transparent border", which 
will impede integration processes between the two republics in 
the area of science, economy and culture. 

</TEXT>

