<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechnya's Dudayev Assesses Russian Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechnya's Dudayev Assesses Russian Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504172694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1350 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Boris Yeltsin is the sole and last stronghold of 
legality in Russia but he might be removed from power soon, 
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev is reported saying at the 
state government's meeting Thursday. Dudayev thought that what 
he described as "certain elite circles in the Russian 
leadership" might make next May the decisive time for Russia. 
  Dudayev said that the Russian leadership consisted of 
factions, each playing its own game, and that his government 
felt this as it tried to have talks on a Russian-Chechen treaty. 
He added that some Russian politicos went as far as negotiating 
with the Chechen opposition. "It would be logical if we 
responded by making contacts with those who oppose the Russian 
leaders but we do not do so for ethical reasons," Dudayev said. 
  Meanwhile, an informed source in the Chechen leadership told 
Interfax that Dudayev was under pressure to discontinue the 
Russo-Chechen talks until an authority emerged in Russia which 
would have the situation under its full control. 

</TEXT>

