<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazia Urges Georgians To Lay Down Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abkhazia Urges Georgians To Lay Down Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504152494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1249 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Irina Shchegoleva and Mikhail </F>
Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Sochi April 15 TASS -- The government of Abkhazia 
has called on the Georgian armed groups, operating in the upper 
part of the Kodor Gorge, to stop hostilities and lay down arms. 
The Abkhazian side, with the participation of U.N. inspectors, 
guarantees the lives and safety of the Georgian groups withdrawn 
from the area. Otherwise, the government of Abkhazia will take 
measures to neutralise "the armed gangs", says a statement 
released by the Abkhazian government today. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned from officials of the press service of 
the Abkhazian Supreme Soviet that this statement was released 
due to the recently increased activity of Georgian armed gangs 
in the Kodor Gorge and in some villages of the Gali district. 
Abkhazian sources report on mortar attacks on the village of 
Lata and raids of armed gangs on the village of Ganakhleba, Gali 
district, which claimed the lives of four men. Several people 
were abducted and their whereabouts are unknown. The Abkhazian 
side believes that such provocations are a violation of the 
Moscow agreements on political measures to settle the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, that they seriously destabilise the 
situation and are intended to torpedo the peaceful negotiations 
and preparations for the repatriation of refugees. 
  The Abkhazian government has announced its readiness to 
ensure the safe evacuation of these groups from the territory of 
the republic if they laid down their arms. 
  In light of the latest developments, the parliament of the 
Abkhazian Republic requested the Russian president and the State 
Duma on Friday not to ratify the Russo-Georgian treaty until the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict is fully settled. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

