<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chisinau Denounces Romanian Criticism of CIS Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chisinau Denounces Romanian Criticism of CIS Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504130794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1207 GMT 15 Apr 95 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev 15 April, TASS -- Official Kishinev 
[Chisinau] expressed a protest against negative reaction of the 
Romanian political circles to the decision of Moldavia [Moldova] 
to join the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  "Everyone should understand that Moldova is an independent 
state and can take any decision," Moldavian President Mircea 
Snegur stated in this connection. 
  Some Romanian law-makers called on their colleagues to 
condemn "the inclusion of the traditional Romanian lands into 
the new Soviet empire," according to the Kishinev radio. 
  Dumitru Motspan, deputy chairman of the Moldavian parliament 
and also the leader of the ruling Agrarian and Democratic Party, 
called Romania's reaction insulting. The recent poll and 
parliamentary elections showed that overwhelming majority of the 
population stood against unification with Romania and for 
independence, he told ITAR- TASS. 
  "We will conclude profitable economic and other agreements 
with all countries of the world, join international unions and 
do not intend to ask anyone's permission for that," Motspan 
stressed. 
  "The inclusion of Moldavia into CIS and the economic union 
would allow it to establish civilized mutual relations with CIS 
countries, to restore old and create new mutually beneficial 
economic links," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

