<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Responds to Criticism of Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Responds to Criticism of Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504171394 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Russian 1400 GMT 
15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Sergey Tereshchenko held a news 
conference in Almaty today. Attending were his first deputy 
Akezhan Kazhegeldin, Economy Minister Mars Urkumbayev, Finance 
Minister Yerkeshbay Derbisov, and National Bank Chairman Daulet 
Sembayev. 
  He stressed that rumors about the lack of a constructive 
governmental program of action were groundless and there was no 
necessity to adopt a new program. It was said that the program 
exists, is viable, and is working already. The president has 
endorsed the anticrisis measures program for 1993-95. At the 
parliament session the government will report about the progress 
of implementation of this program. The Cabinet of Ministers is 
working in conformity with the adopted plan. Its work is 
described in the statement on the economic policy for 1994 which 
was published. 
  Besides, in conformity with the president's instruction, a 
group led by the first deputy prime minister was set up which is 
examining the alternative programs of economic development and 
reform in Kazakhstan, submitted by the opposition parties. 
Members of the government, answering questions, touched upon a 
number of topical problems in the implementation of these 
reforms. In particular, the measures to enhance the national 
currency were discussed, as well as state loans and credits, 
foreign financial aid for entrepreneurship, and the introduction 
of the new taxation system. Also discussed were enforceable 
enactments adopted of late on abolishing natural [as heard] 
allowances for some categories of the population, increase of 
minimum wages and pensions, and further state policy regarding 
the public welfare of citizens with low income. 

</TEXT>

