<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Landsbergis Happy With President's Strasbourg Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Landsbergis Happy With President's Strasbourg Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1504185194 Tallinn BNS in English 1502 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1504185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Apr 15, BNS -- Vytautas Landsbergis, 
leader of the Lithuanian parliament's rightist opposition, 
expressed satisfaction with Lithuanian President Algirdas 
Brazauskas' speech at the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council 
of Europe in Strasbourg Thursday [14 April]. 
  "Most probably it was the first time that the head of the 
Lithuanian state criticized Russia's policy and leadership," 
Landsbergis told a news conference Friday. 
  In his words, until now, Lithuania carried out a timeserving 
policy with respect to Moscow. "I now see that the leadership of 
the LDLP (Lithuanian Democratic Labor Party) understands 
Russia's actual policy," Landsbergis said. 
  The opposition leader said he is not certain that the LDLP 
has decided to view things realistically, but such indications 
exist. 
  Landsbergis said a realistic view means "to give up 
"Moscowcentrism," inherited from Soviet times, when Moscow is 
understood as the big center where Lithuania's fate is decided. 
  "Possibilities to form not a post-communist-single-party, 
but 
a national policy may then appear." 

</TEXT>

