Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Deems Soviet Soldiers' Naturalization Unlawful </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Deems Soviet Soldiers' Naturalization Unlawful </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1504110394 Tallinn BNS in English 0914 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1504110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] VILNIUS, Apr 15, BNS - The Constitutional Court of 
Lithuania established that the parliament's decision allowing 
naturalization of former Soviet servicemen as Lithuanian 
citizens violates the Lithuanian Constitution. 
  According to an amendment to the citizenship law, adopted by 
the parliament last year, persons who served in Soviet armed 
forces and other repressive structures may be granted Lithuanian 
citizenship, provided they ceased service before March 1, 1992 
and received Lithuanian citizen certificates before Nov. 4, 1991. 
  The court said dual citizenship is possible only in 
exceptional cases, while former Soviet servicemen were Soviet 
citizens and received Lithuanian citizenship certificates 
unlawfully. 
  According to unofficial reports, the amendment to the 
citizenship law may have affected around 800 former servicemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

