Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Says Kiev To Take `Active Part' in Economic Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Says Kiev To Take `Active Part' in Economic Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504123694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1055 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk has said that 
Kiev will take an active part in a CIS economic union. In an 
interview with INTERFAX he said that he would sign documents on 
an associated membership. 
  Kravchuk believes that now the difference between full and 
associated membership in the economic union is only relative. 
  "I have looked through economic documents prepared for the 
Moscow CIS summit. We shall sign them. Like full members, we 
shall put our signatures under the documents on the economic 
cooperation among the CIS members," said Kravchuk. 
  Asked to express his attitude to the initiative by 
Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev on the creation of a 
Euro-Asian union, Kravchuk said that today the integration in 
such a scope, proposed by some politicians, following the 
example of the European Union, has no basis. 
  For a Euro-Asian union to work, conditions should be 
prepared 
gradually, said Kravchuk. It is no secret that it took European 
countries 35 years to form the European Union. The CIS has 
existed only several years and we did not yet form many 
mechanisms for the Commonwealth to work. There are also other 
problems which are not solved, not for a lack of will. The 
conditions are not ripe for a Euro-Asian union, said Kravchuk. 
  Kravchuk said that he was not against the idea of a 
Euro-Asian union. He said he did not want the idea to 
materialize now, because, he believes, it would lead nowhere. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

