<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges `More Thought' on Joining PFP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges `More Thought' on Joining PFP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704142094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1230 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Before leaving Moscow for Belgrade, Saturday, 
Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev told Interfax more 
thought should be given to plans to join NATO's Partnership for 
Peace [PFP] program. 
  Kozyrev wished allied aircraft had refrained from bombing 
Serb positions near Gorazde pending consultations with Moscow. 
He said Russia and NATO had agreed to launch special, 
gentlemanly, relations on the basis of a more or less standard 
pilot document. 
  According to Kozyrev, Russia wanted more than the end of 
hostile relations with NATO. It wanted NATO to either learn to 
promote full-scale cooperation with Russia or set thought on 
integration into a mechanism that would be suited to meet new 
reality. He wanted NATO to treat Russia as a great power. 
  And, Kozyrev would want Russia and NATO to promote more 
serious and constructive relations in addition to signing a 
pilot document of limited importance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

