<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments on Gorazde Following Belgrade Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Comments on Gorazde Following Belgrade Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Optimistic on Results of Pale Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD1704154494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1526 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 17 TASS -- Talks between U.N. special 
envoy Yasushi Akashi and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, 
which got under way in the Sarajevo suburb of Pale with the 
participation of Russian mediator Vitaliy Churkin, are to result 
in pullback of troops from around Gorazde, consolidation of the 
U.N. designated "safe area" around the town and putting the 
areas under U.N. control, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev told reporters upon returning from Belgrade. 
  Earlier in the day, Kozyrev met with the Serb leadership to 
set priorities in the proposed settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Serb President Slobodan Milosevic assured the Russian 
diplomat that Serbs were ready to enter talks to find a peaceful 
solution to the crisis around Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

