<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Seeks `More Substantive' Accord With NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Seeks `More Substantive' Accord With NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704163294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1600 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, April 17 (TASS) -- "Partnership with the 
North Atlantic Alliance was our choice from the very outset", 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev told reporters after 
returning from a 24-hour trip to Belgrade. 
  "Two years ago, Russian President Boris Yeltsin sent a 
letter 
to NATO, offering partnership and close cooperation, and at 
present we are seeking for the best ways of promoting these 
ties", he said commenting on Russia's approach towards NATO's 
partnership for peace programme. 
  We are ready to discuss whether a framework agreement should 
be signed first, which is to be followed by a broader one, or 
whether we should conclude a broader partnership pact, without 
signing a preliminary agreement, Kozyrev noted. 
  "What is clear is that we want a more serious and 
substantive 
agreement adequate to relations that should exist between NATO 
and the superpower of Russia...especially an agreement which 
will exclude unilateral actions, particulary military ones, in 
areas where we have to closely cooperate", he said. 
  The Russian Government has agreed in principle to join the 
NATO plan, which offers East European and former Soviet states 
cooperation but stops short of letting them join the alliance. 
  Kozyrev has postponed his visit to Brussels on April 21 to 
sign the Partnership for Peace deal, apparantly angered by 
NATO's air strikes on Serb forces in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

