<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Continues `Tough' Talks in Sarajevo, Pale </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Continues `Tough' Talks in Sarajevo, Pale </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604143394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1251 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1604143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As Interfax has learned from Russia's Foreign 
Ministry, the Russian President's Special Envoy, Deputy Foreign 
Minister Vitaliy Churkin arrived in Sarajevo on Saturday to help 
end hostilities and reconcile Serbs and Moslems in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  In the words of a senior Russian diplomat, the negotiations 
have been quite tough, although the sides have revealed some 
encouraging signs. 
  Nonetheless, in his opinion, the achievement of an agreement 
within the next two-three days is hardly possible for political, 
military, and technical reasons. An accord must fix a 
disengagement line between the Serbs and the Moslems, a line 
which in their view, could be a frontier for a long time. The 
negotiators have been bargaining for virtually each mile of the 
mountain terrain. This does not portend a quick completion of 
the negotiating process, the diplomat said. 
  However, he did not rule out that an accord could be signed 
already next week. 

</TEXT>

