Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Fails To Achieve Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Fails To Achieve Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804130594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1220 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Naryshkin] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb April 18 TASS -- Russian envoy to former 
Yugoslavia Vitaliy Churkin failed to talk Bosnian Serbs into 
ceasing their offensive on Gorazde and warned them that attempts 
to seize the city would trigger mass bloodshed. 
  "My only hope is that fire will no longer be opened on the 
town. It would be a huge catastrophe to try and seize it -- this 
would result in an immense bloodshed", he told reporters before 
leaving for Moscow Monday. Churkin arrived in Zagreb from 
Sarajevo. 
  The situation around the Muslim enclave in Bosnia "is poorly 
manageable and completely unexplainable in any reasonable and 
logical terms", he stressed. 
  During his eight-day trip Churkin tried to ensure "a serious 
agreement on ceasing hostilities along the whole of the 
Serbian-Muslim front and proceed to a political settlement and, 
what was always important for the Serbs, to a practical 
beginning of the lifting of sanctions". 
  "Only one thing was demanded from the Serbs in the given 
situation -- to stop their offensive on Gorazde", Churkin said 
and added "unfortunately, they failed to do that". 
  "Defence of Gorazde has collapsed. It is surrounded by 
Serbs. We worried all day yesterday whether they would open 
fire. Luckily they fired only four mines. The situation was 
very tense when three tanks approached the city. Had they 
fired, NATO could have resumed air strikes", he said. 
  According to Churkin, Serbs have reportedly agreed to allow 
the evacuation of the sick from Gorazde, "but for the time being 
we are afraid to do that as the arrival of helicopters can cause 
panic among refugees". 
  Churkin refused to predict further developments in Gorazde. 
He only said that "if they get out of this humanitarian deadend 
we shall see how the developments go". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16553 </DOCNO>
