<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Blocks Further Air Strikes on Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Blocks Further Air Strikes on Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604154894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1519 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1604154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Kondrashov] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, 16 Apr -- Today the Russian side blocked 
new NATO air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions in the Gorazde 
region. 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned from well-informed 
sources that in the first half of today U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher telephoned Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev and told him that NATO aircraft were preparing to carry 
out strikes against Serbs firing on Gorazde. 
  Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian president's special 
representative, who was in Pale, a Bosnian Serb-controlled 
suburb of Sarajevo, was informed of the content of the 
conversation between Christopher and Kozyrev. 
  Following his contacts with the Bosnian Serb leadership and 
UN forces command, V. Churkin announced that Serb shelling of 
Gorazde was not an issue. Only four mortar explosions had been 
recorded in the town, and UN observers were unable to determine 
precisely which side had fired them. 
  In addition, General Ratko Mladic, the Serb Army commander, 
has assured V. Churkin that Serb forces do not intend to storm 
Gorazde or bring artillery fire to bear on the town. 
  Information received from the Russian president's special 
representative was forwarded to W. Christopher, after which the 
order for NATO air strikes on Serb positions near Gorazde was 
rescinded, the abovementioned sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

