<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kiev Warned Over Fleet Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kiev Warned Over Fleet Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604103394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1102 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1604103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 16 Apr (ITAR-TASS) -- After the meeting of 
the Russian and Ukrainian presidents, Boris Yeltsin and Leonid 
Kravchuk, where an agreement on a stage-by-stage settlement of 
the Black Sea fleet issue was signed, the Ukrainian side has 
begun to interpret the accords that have been achieved in its 
typical cavalier manner. Even before the talks provided for in 
the agreement, where the parameters of how the fleet is to be 
divided are to be discussed, the Ukrainian side began to put 
forward through the mass media its own options of the lease 
itself, its length, and the locations where the Russian Black 
Sea Fleet is to be based, says a statement by Vyacheslav 
Kostikov, the press secretary of the Russian president. In it, 
Kostikov said the following: 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin yesterday stated during the 
talks that he does not accept the haggling tone, which is 
lowering the level of relations and trust. The Russian side has 
to remind Ukraine once again about the harsh realities and 
imperatives that underline the agreement just signed. Careless 
words and actions are out of place here when the Black Sea Fleet 
is at stake. Moscow urges the Kiev politicians and the military 
not to embark on unilateral actions that could cast doubt on the 
sincerity of the negotiation process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

