<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Air Power Questioned After Iraq Incident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Air Power Questioned After Iraq Incident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1604083094 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 16 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK1604083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Pogorelyy report: "An Accidental Error or a </F>
Logical Tragedy?"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] The first impression from the 
tragedy in the Iraqi skies was: An impossible, tragic mistake 
has occurred. The situation, however, gives rise to a number of 
legitimate questions. Answers to them may not be the most 
pleasant for the U.S. military establishment. 
  First, about the pilots' professional level. Judging by 
their initial testimony, they mistook U.S.-made UH-60 Blackhawk 
helicopters for Iraqi Soviet-built Mi-8's. Indeed, outwardly 
they bear a remote resemblance, but with the slightest doubts, 
were the pilots not supposed to fly around what they saw as 
suspicious objects and make sure what it was, friend or foe? 
Moreover, were they not supposed to activate their Friend or 
Foe identification system? If none of this was done, the 
logical conclusion is: The fighters used the very first 
opportunity to show the Iraqis who is master in their airspace. 
  The second question and the answer to it bears on the 
performance characteristics of U.S. combat aviation. If the 
F-15 pilots used the interrogator after all, did they therefore 
receive no confirmation that the targets were not friendly? In 
addition, as Lieutenant General Richard Keller, chief of staff 
of the U.S. Command Europe -- responsible for the military part 
of operation Provide Comfort-2 -- who was summoned to the 
Pentagon explained, at the time of the incident airspace to the 
north of the 36th parallel was monitored by AWACS aircraft. 
Their onboard radars and computers are designed precisely to 
detect and track air targets and guide the interceptors onto 
them. In other words, one cannot rule out a malfunction in the 
operation of these "super modern arms and equipment systems" 
which are so zealously promoted by the Americans. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

