<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Visits Military Installation in Vietnam </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation Visits Military Installation in Vietnam </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604224494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1615 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1604224494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Blagov] </F>
  [Text] Hanoi, 16 Apr -- The Russian Government delegation 
headed by Deputy Chairman of the Russian Federation Government 
Yuriy Yarov today visited a Russian military installation in Cam 
Ranh Bay in Vietnam. 
  Answering questions from the ITAR-TASS correspondent on the 
eve of the visit, the Russian deputy prime minister praised the 
present state of bilateral cooperation in the military field, a 
new impetus to which was, in his words, given by a visit to 
Russia in March by [Lieutenant General] Dao Dinh Luyen, chief of 
the General Staff of the Vietnamese People's Army. Yarov noted 
that the visit to Cam Ranh Bay was purely fact-finding. At the 
same time, he said that the visit could result in new proposals 
on joint mutually beneficial use of the installation, even 
though the problem had not been discussed in the course of the 
present visit to Vietnam. 
  The materials and machinery supplies station at Cam Ranh 
peninsula is at present used by Russia on the basis of the 
agreement signed by the former USSR and Vietnam in 1981. It 
expires in 2004. The numbers of the Russian staff servicing the 
installation have been reduced by about three-quarters compared 
with 1980, while cooperation with the Vietnamese side has been 
transferred to a commercial basis. 

</TEXT>

