<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Decrees Protection for National Cinema </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Decrees Protection for National Cinema </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604151694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1251 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1604151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Second Congress of Russian Cinema Workers opened 
in Moscow on Saturday. A message from President Yeltsin to its 
participants stresses that "the unique potential of Russian 
cinema must be preserved at all costs." 
  On Friday, he signed a decree on a protectionist state 
policy 
in the national cinema art. Support for cinema is recognized in 
this document as crucial to the government's cultural 
development plans. The decree obliges the cabinet to set aside 
funds for the national motion-picture industry and submit a bill 
on national cinema to the Federal Assembly within three months. 
  There are nearly 300 film-makers at the forum in Moscow. 
Secretary of Russia's Cinematographic Union Sergey Solovyev, a 
film director, spoke about the Russian cinema's plight and ways 
to overcome it. The congress will last two days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

