<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Monetary Union With Russia Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reactions to Monetary Union With Russia Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Prime Minister's Reaction </H4>

<F P=102> LD1504152094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1233 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM correspondent Yekaterina Vysotskaya for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Minsk 15 April, TASS -- "One should not be afraid 
that the foreign capital will turn its back to its Belarussian 
[Belarusian] partners because of the agreement with Russia. 
Honest investors, for whom partnership with Belarus is a matter 
of economy, not politics, have already come to our country, and 
the unification of the Belarussian and Russian markets will not 
influence those relations," Belarussian Prime Minister 
Vyacheslav Kebich said at a news conference. 
  He pointed out that problems connected with relations 
between 
Belarus and third countries are not coordinated with Russia. 
This is why it is for Belarus to decide whether to take foreign 
credits or not. 
  Responding to the question of journalists about the reaction 
of the International Monetary Fund to the signing of the 
agreement, Kebich said: "A letter that we received before the 
signing of the documents reaffirmed, that the IMF would continue 
to cooperate with us. Moreover, the letter asked to decide more 
quickly whether we join the rouble zone or not. So, our foreign 
partners were also waiting for an answer to the question: Shall 
we enter the rouble zone or not?" 

</TEXT>

