<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis on Requirements for Russian Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ulmanis on Requirements for Russian Troop Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504194894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1628 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Guntis Ulmanis speaking in Riga said the 
signing of a package deal with Moscow on Russian troop 
withdrawals was largely hinged on a solution to the problem of 
repatriation of retired servicemen of Russia and the former 
Soviet Union residing in Latvia. 
  To bring this about, the negotiating teams will have to 
amend 
the initialled agreement on social security nets for retired 
Russian servicemen with permanent residence in Latvia, Ulmanis 
said. Ulmanis also considers it necessary to create an 
international support fund by Latvia, Russia and western 
countries to help towards voluntary repatriation of Russian 
servicemen (The Latvian government on Thursday had approved 
Ulmanis' proposal to set up an appropriate working group-IF). 
Nothing short of this can help defuse tension over the issue of 
retired servicemen whose presence here is widely seen as being 
undesirable, Ulmanis said. 
  He thinks the fund can also help repatriate 180,000 
non-Latvians who are willing to settle in Russia and other CIS 
states. The signing of the pullout agreement will be 
complicated unless the repatriation issue is resolved, Ulmanis 
said. 
  IF Note: The initialled agreement binds Latvia to ensure 
continued residence and non-discrimination of retired Russian 
servicemen in areas such social security and medical care. 
Official counts put the number of such pensioners at 22,000 
with 3,500 of them granted Latvian citizenship. 
  Ulmanis reiterated that no agreement would be signed with 
Moscow until the Russian president recalled his decree of April 
5 providing for the setting up of a Russian army base in Latvia. 
He considers it to be a tactical move to probe a possible 
reaction from Latvia and the West rather than a mistake as 
Russian officials try to present the decree. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16599 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov075_u_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-075 </AU>
