<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Amendments to Immigration Laws Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Amendments to Immigration Laws Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1604132094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 16 Apr 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1604132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report] </F>
  [Text] An extraordinary session of the government has 
passed amendments to the law on foreigners and stateless persons 
entering and staying in Latvia, and related to this law addenda 
to the law on police which envisions the creation of emigration 
police within the framework of the state police. Inese 
Birznietse, the Saeima human rights commission chairperson, 
explained that the amendments passed in accordance with the 
rules provided for by Article 81... apply to persons who arrived 
in Latvia illegally, and have been passed with an eye to 
improving the procedure for their expulsion from the country. 
The amendments to the law were fully agreed on with the CSCE 
mission but their final version have not been passed in Latvia, 
for which reason it has been impossible today to find out 
exactly what the expulsion procedure is and how one can appeal 
against it. Still, according to Birznietse, mass deportations 
are out of the question because the amendments also contain a 
reservation that they are not applicable to persons whose legal 
status in Latvia has not been determined and in whose regard 
legislation has so far not been brought into line. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

