<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Rages in Nagorno-Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting Rages in Nagorno-Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804150694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Azerbaijani Army on Monday [18 April] morning 
resumed attacks on Nagorno-Karabakh positions in the Mardakert, 
Martuni and Fizuli sectors of the front, a Nagorno-Karabakh 
military source said. 
  He told INTERFAX fighting was still in progress at noon. 
  On Sunday, intense fighting was going on on a large section 
of the front in Mardakert and Fizuli Districts. 
  The source said Nagorno-Karabakh forces had rebuffed all the 
strikes and had switched over to launching counterattacks in 
some areas, mainly in Mardakert District where it had destroyed 
some of the Azerbaijani firing positions. 
  The source denied Azerbaijani reports that hundreds of 
Nagorno-Karabakh troops had been killed. He said Azerbaijan's 
losses had been much heavier than Nagorno-Karabakh's. 
  Meanwhile, the Azerbaijani Defense Ministry said that, on 
Sunday afternoon, Armenian tank units positioned in northern 
Nagorno-Karabakh had made several attempts to advance towards 
the town of Terter, but were stopped by Azerbaijani forces, 
which destroyed six Armenian tanks and seized another two pieces 
of new armor. 
  Early on Monday morning, the Armenians once again tried to 
break through to Terter, simultaneously attacking villages close 
to the town, but were thrown back around 0800 after heavy 
fighting, losing three tanks, one armored personnel carrier and 
about 90 troops, the ministry said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

