<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Uzbekistan, China Agree To Restore Great Silk Way </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Uzbekistan, China Agree To Restore Great Silk Way </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904100794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0932 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tashkent April 19 ITAR-TASS -- The expansion of 
bilateral trade and economic cooperation and the restoration of 
the ancient silk way linking China to the Central Asian 
countries was in the focus of talks between President Islam 
Karimov of Uzbekistan and Chinese Premier Li Peng here today. 
Chinese diplomats in the Uzbek capital told ITAR-TASS that the 
talks also deal with regional and international problems. 
  On Tuesday morning the Chinese premier laid flowers at the 
monument to great poet and thinker Alisher Navoy. 
  Both countries now have more ground for further deepening 
friendly relations, Islam Karimov said at the state dinner in 
honour of the Chinese leader on Monday. He called on the 
numerous entrepreneurs, who accompanied the Chinese premier to 
establish direct ties with enterprises in Uzbekistan. Islam 
Karimov pointed to "great successes of the great Chinese people" 
in reforming their economy and said that "the people of 
Uzbekistan have a great interest in everything that is taking 
place in China". 
  According to Karimov, Li Peng's visit contributes to the 
beginning of a new era in relations between the two countries. 
  Li Peng recalled that the two countries are "close 
neighbours 
and countries with ancient civilisations" and said a new period 
of relations between them began after Uzbekistan proclaimed 
independence. China, he stressed, needs "a good international 
situation to accomplish its own modernisation. For this reason 
China pays great attention to the development of relations with 
the neighbouring countries. 
  The Chinese premier supported the proposal to restore the 
silk way as a means of developing trade, economic and cultural 
ties between the two countries. "China intends to make efforts 
to achieve this end," he said. 
  China, a considerable part of whose territory, particularly 
the Xinjiang Uygur autonomous region, is populated by Muslims, 
is seriously concerned about the spread of Islamic 
fundamentalism in the Asian republics of the former USSR. 
Xinjiang has long been known as harbouring strong separatist 
tendencies under Islamic slogans. 
  Li Peng, whose foreign trip will also take him to 
Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan and Mongolia, is being 
accompanied on the tour by chairman of the State Committee for 
Nationalities Ismail Aimat, an ethnic Uygur, who stands for the 
country's Muslim population in the Chinese leadership. 
  The head of the Chinese Government arrived for a three-day 
official visit to the capital of Uzbekistan on Monday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

