<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation Remains `Complex' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation Remains `Complex' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604160394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1251 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1604160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The situation on the Tajik-Afghan border remains 
complex. Some field commanders from the antigovernment 
opposition and the Islamic Rebirth Movement plan to attack 
border installations and plant field mines in Tajikistan along 
the border with Afghanistan. 
  As the Tajik Foreign Ministry's Spokesman Zafar Saidov 
disclosed at a briefing in Dushanbe on Saturday, the foreign 
department had received from the Afghan Embassy in Russia a 
note, which says that the Afghan Defence Ministry is ready to 
take the situation in the Imam-Sakhi (the Kunduz province) under 
control. It was from that area that Tajik militants shelled a 
border check point at Nizhny Pyanj on 11 April. The Afghan 
Defence Ministry pledged to do all it can to prevent such 
actions, Saidov said. 
  He also reported that the Afghan authorities had asked the 
Tajik leadership to step up joint actions and stabilize the 
situation on the border. 

</TEXT>

