<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rosa Otunbayeva Appointed Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rosa Otunbayeva Appointed Foreign Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804200594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1831 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 18 April TASS -- The Kyrgyz Parliament 
appointed Rosa Otunbayeva Kyrgyz foreign minister on Monday [18 
April]. 
  Otunbayeva is a graduate of the Moscow State University's 
Faculty of Philosophy and holds a candidate's degree in 
philosophy. She was a lecturer at the national university. For 
over five years she worked in district committees of the 
Republic's capital. 
  Roza Otunbayeva, 44, held the posts of the deputy chairman 
of 
the Kyrgyz Transport Ministry and Ministry of External Affairs 
during the Soviet era. 
  She worked in the USSR Ministry of Foreign Affairs since 
1989, and one year later was appointed chairperson of the Soviet 
Union's Commission of UNESCO Affairs. Later she worked as 
vice-president of the executive council of this international 
organisation. 
  She was ambassador of Kyrgyzia [Kyrgyzstan] to the United 
States from February, 1992 when the republic became an 
independent state. According to specialists, Otunbayeva is an 
active supporter of aggressive diplomacy. She speaks fluently 
German and English. 
  Lately the Kyrgyz Government had no head of the foreign 
department. The January session of the Parliament did not show 
confidence in Foreign Minister Ednan Karabayev who was 
recommended at this post by President Askar Akayev. 
  The new appointment has been made on the eve of Chinese 
Premier Li Peng's visit to Kirghizia. 

</TEXT>

