<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Parliament Session Begins 18 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Parliament Session Begins 18 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Picketers Surround Parliament Building </H4>

<F P=102> LD1904082694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0700 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904082694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty 19 April, TASS -- The new Supreme Soviet of 
Kazakhstan began work here today morning. It will be half the 
size of the previous parliament and will work on a permanent 
professional basis. 
  The MP's, who have won their mandates during the 7 March 
elections, are to decide some organisational questions first, 
particularly the structural pattern of the parliament. They are 
also to elect their speaker. Then the parliament will go over 
to the endorsement of the agenda and to the discussion of the 
items included in it. 
  But this may prove to be a difficult job. Several parties 
and public movements of the republic have declared that they 
would join the opposition against the present executive 
authorities. And if the MP's, sharing their views, decide to 
form their own blocs, the Supreme Soviet will hardly be able to 
avoid an acute factional struggle for power from the very outset. 
  The MP's will also be influenced by the situation around 
parliament house. More than 300 veterans of war and labor, 
invalids, and representatives of work collectives are picketing 
it from early morning today. They demand better living 
conditions, steps to curb the inflation and growing prices. A 
large meeting began there a short while ago. Its participants 
are protesting against the government's economic and social 
policy, which has placed many people far below the poverty line. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

