<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov: Civic Accord Signing on 28 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov: Civic Accord Signing on 28 April </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804181194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1740 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 18 TASS -- "The signing of an agreement 
on civic peace and accord will take place on April 28 in the St. 
George hall of the Grand Kremlin Palace," Russian presidential 
chief of staff Sergey Filatov said on Monday. In an interview 
with ITAR-TASS, Filatov said that the agreement will be signed 
by President Boris Yeltsin, the government, leaders of the State 
Duma and the Federation Council, and representatives of trade 
unions, the presidential public chamber, religious organisations 
and political movements. 
  "The agreement will remain open to all who may wish to sign 
it," Filatov added. A special conciliatory commission which 
will comprise "representatives of the president, the government, 
political parties and public movements" will oversee the 
implementation of the agreement. Filatov believes that the 
commission should use the experience of the mass media court. 
  He said there is no need to adopt the agreement on civic 
peace and accord as a federal law, but added that the parties to 
it may face possible consequences if they violate the agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

