<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray on Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray on Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804180294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Vice Premier Sergey Shakhray said there was 
no alternative to the idea of national accord proposed by the 
Russian president. He stressed in an interview with an Interfax 
correspondent in Novosibirsk that this provided for real accord 
aimed at restoring the political and economic stability in 
Russia and not just for a one-time peace agreement between 
different political parties and movements. Shakhray is currently 
in Novosibirsk where he is taking part in a scientific 
conference on regional economic issues on the invitation of the 
local administration. 
  Shakhray pointed out that many political parties and 
movements, their factions in the Federal Assembly and 
representatives of the regional authorities were struggling for 
spheres of influence in Russia's energy, military-industrial and 
agrarian complexes. Shakhray believes that the president and the 
government must act as mediators in order not to let any 
political forces worsen the situation in the Russian economy. 
Shakhray emphasized that only this agreement could bring 
economic stability to Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

