<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy: Troops Should Down NATO Planes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy: Troops Should Down NATO Planes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804175294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The only way of ending violence in the Balkans is to 
send one Russian army division to each of the five former 
Yugoslav republics and bring down any NATO warplane before it 
flies over the region, LDP [Liberal Democratic Party] leader 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy said on Monday. 
  He held out promises of an immediate peace in the Balkans, 
Georgia and Nagorno-Karabakh as soon as his party came to 
office. Zhirinovskiy, who is confident about LDP's chances of 
power, outlined plans of sending Russian crack units, now 
withdrawn from Germany, to ex-Yugoslavia. "Trainloads of troops 
will head for Belgrade instead of eastwards, there will be calm 
and quiet in the Balkans where the Russian Army will remain 
forever", he promised. 
  On Moscow's rescheduling of Russia's entry of the 
Partnership 
for Peace plan, the LDP leader accused the foreign ministry and 
President Yeltsin of procrastination saying "their decisions 
come only after thousands of people have died". 
  He is also confident that Moscow will cancel planned 
exercises with US troops in the Urals scheduled for July. The 
forthcoming event is of public concern and our people should not 
have any cause for anxiety, he said. 

</TEXT>

