<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin `Personal Diary' To Appear in May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin `Personal Diary' To Appear in May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1904081994 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 16 Apr 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> PM1904081994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report in the VEKHI section: "Boris Yeltsin's </F>
New Book"] 
  [Text] Boris Yeltsin's new book "A President's Notes" 
[Zapiski Prezidenta] will appear in the bookstores in Russia and 
in more than 30 other countries in May. 
  "This is a large book," Lev Gushchin, the chief editor, 
stressed, "with over 400 pages and 100 color photographs. It is 
written in the form of the president's personal diary and covers 
the events from the dramatic August of 1991 to the tragic 
October of 1993. Descriptions of the events are interspersed in 
the book with Boris Nikolayevich's reflections on the paths of 
Russia's development and transformation, portraits of political 
figures and those people with whose lives the country's destiny 
became interlinked at that difficult period." 
  "It would be no mistake," Lev Gushchin noted, "to say that 
the many facts and assessments contained in the book are really 
sensational and that many of the riddles and mysteries of recent 
years are logically answered here. But to be frank it is the 
tone the `Notes' which is most impressive. This is perhaps the 
first time that we have encountered a text which is so personal, 
candid, and at times merciless toward the author and others, a 
text penned by a member of the country's top leadership." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

