<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gorbachev Compares Policies to Khrushchev's `Thaw' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gorbachev Compares Policies to Khrushchev's `Thaw' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804105494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0958 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 18 TASS -- Former Soviet President 
Mikhail Gorbachev compared his "perestroyka" which was aimed to 
reform the Soviet totalitarian system to the liberalisation of 
his predecessor Nikita Khrushchev, often called as the "thaw", 
which exposed and condemned the personality cult of Joseph 
Stalin and introduced limited freedom in the country. Gorbachev 
also admitted that he knew he could be ousted like Khrushchev. 
Khrushchev was toppled in 1964 after his reformist plans caused 
a major opposition from hard-line communist party nomenklatura. 
  "We remembered the experience of Khrushchev, but we 
underestimated the reactionary forces of the past", Gorbachev 
said addressing a conference devoted to the 100th birth 
anniversary of Khrushchev which opened in the Gorbachev 
Foundation on Monday. He added that yet in 1987, two years 
after perestroyka began, "the people who started the 
transformations realised that the fate of Khrushchev was in 
store for them". Gorbachev had to step down after his communist 
elite staged a coup against him in August 1991 which resulted in 
the collapse of the Soviet Union. 
  The former Soviet leader stressed that Khrushchev had a 
great 
influence on all the Soviet reformers. He compared his 
perestroyka to Khrushchev's "thaw" and said that the latter 
failed because the new policy was implemented by old methods. 
"Problems of immense historic importance cannot be solved by 
Bolshevik methods", Gorbachev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

