<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan To Divide Defense Ministry, General Staff </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plan To Divide Defense Ministry, General Staff </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1904080094 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 19 Apr 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1904080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Dmitriy Kholodov report: "The Secret of the President's </F>
Safe. `Tanks Advance by Two to Three Men'"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] As MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS has 
learned from reliable sources, a new military reform plan is 
already lying in the president's safe. In this context, 
military experts suppose that in the very near future the 
question of separating the Defense Ministry from the General 
Staff will be raised again. There are also indications that the 
plan provides for the creation of a powerful ideological body 
like the old Main Personnel Directorate [Glavpur]. Former 
presidential military adviser Gen. Volkogonov and Gen. 
Vladimirov, the Yeltsin team's main analyst on military affairs, 
are cited among the document's authors. 
  The new plan has been attributed such a high security 
classification (a stamp saying, "Burn before reading" [as 
published] that even some members of the Security Council do not 
know about it yet. Still, signs are that many do not know how 
current reforms are proceeding in the army either. 
  Even people in the Defense Ministry itself do not know. 
Generals from the Defense Ministry, who only a month ago were 
talking about a "phased" reform plan, are now reminiscent of 
hedgehogs wandering in the fog [reference to a popular animated 
cartoon]. Now the Defense Ministry discusses the disbandment of 
the Baltic Fleet, ruling to preserve it. Now they effectively 
abolish the Air Defense Force, having the public believe that 
the troops will remain. It is also reported that the main 
commands will be abolished, for instance the Main Ground Force 
Command. In brief, as has always been the case with military 
strategists, "tanks advance by two to three men." 
  Gen. Vladimirov, whom we asked to comment on the rumor about 
the new reform plan, confirmed that "conceptually, no one 
understands which reform the Defense Ministry is now pursuing." 
He is convinced that the ministry should be separated from the 
General Staff. In Russia, frequent changes of government and 
therefore defense ministers are simply inevitable. According to 
Aleksandr Vladimirov, the army must be safeguarded from this 
leapfrog approach, and the General Staff given the right to 
issue orders directly to the troops. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

