<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warns Serbs Not To Test World's Patience </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Warns Serbs Not To Test World's Patience </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904111394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1035 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Sergey Babkin and </F>
Yuriy Tyssovskiy] 
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- "I would most resolutely recommend 
to the Serbian side not to test the patience of the world 
community," Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said today. 
He was speaking to journalists at a news conference after his 
talks with Yasir 'Arafat, chairman of the PLO Executive 
Committee and president of the Palestinian State. 
  It goes without saying, the Russian foreign policy chief 
said, that we call for restraint from all sides in the conflict. 
  Kozyrev spoke highly of the initiative by French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe, with whom he had a telephone conversation 
this morning. A. Juppe has proposed that Russia, the United 
States, the European Union, and the United Nations work out, 
once and for all, a united stand on the conflict in Bosnia. 
Andrey Kozyrev called this proposal "highly promising and 
timely." We have long been striving for this, he said, and we 
hope that under the present critical circumstances our American 
friends and partners will treat this initiative seriously. 
Ultimately, this is the minimum we have to achieve -- to have a 
united and well-considered political stand. This could form the 
basis for the formulation of demands to the warring sides, and, 
at the same time, for initiatives that would open up 
opportunities for them, specifically, the lifting of sanctions 
as the demands of the world community are met. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

