<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma's Rybkin Meets Finnish Leaders in Helsinki </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma's Rybkin Meets Finnish Leaders in Helsinki </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Discusses Bosnia With Foreign Minister </H4>

<F P=102> LD1804164494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1039 
GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Tamara Zamyatina and Vladimir </F>
Mostovets] 
  [Text] Helsinki, 18 Apr -- Russo-Finnish relations, 
prospects for Russia's entry in the Council of Europe, and 
settlement of the Bosnia-Herzegovina conflict were topical at 
today's meeting between Russia's State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin 
and Finnish Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto. Ivan Rybkin is 
visiting Finland at the head of a Russian parliamentary 
delegation. 
  During the discussion the two sides expressed concern over 
mounting tensions in Bosnia and voiced their common viewpoint 
view that the conflict in former Yugoslavia must be settled 
through negotiations and not through the use of force. Ivan 
Rybkin stressed that any use of military force can only be 
permitted with UN approval and following mandatory consultations 
with all permanent members of the UN Security Council. 
  While discussing Russia's entry into the Council of Europe, 
the State Duma chairman and the Finnish foreign minister noted 
that this step would be in the interests of the entire region, 
since Russia cannot be sidelined in European integration 
process. Heikki Haavisto reaffirmed Finland's commitment to 
contribute toward Russia's speedy acceptance into the Council of 
Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

