<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Intransigent' U.S. Policy in Iraq Criticized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Intransigent' U.S. Policy in Iraq Criticized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1804135794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 16 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1804135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Sychev report: "Pentagon Asks Airmen in Iraq to </F>
Be Less Aggressive"] 
  [Excerpts] The 26 people on board the two U.S. helicopters 
downed by U.S. fighters over Northern Iraq probably died as the 
result of a mistake by the fighter pilots or technical faults. 
They were the victims of Washington's intransigent anti-Iraqi 
policy. 
  The two Black Hawk helicopters with U.S., British, French, 
and Turkish officers from the UN mission on board were flying to 
a meeting with the Kurdish insurgent leader Salakhaddin when 
they were shot down in broad daylight by two missiles fired from 
the two F-15 fighters. [passage omitted] 
  The war against Iraq ended in 1991, but Washington's policy 
toward Iraq remains warlike in tone and is marked by an 
unconcealed hostility toward Baghdad. It is patently obvious 
that the U.S. airmen, who were monitoring the safe haven in 
northern Iraq which was created soon after the Persian Gulf 
campaign to prevent Iraqi air raids on Kurdish camps, were 
influenced by the mood of official Washington. It is no 
coincidence that the Pentagon has issued several orders aimed at 
"curbing the aggressiveness" of the U.S. airmen serving in the 
safe havens in south and north Iraq and in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16700 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov075_a_94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mutual Concessions on Black Sea Fleet Urged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mutual Concessions on Black Sea Fleet Urged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904083394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0702 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS military analyst Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 19 TASS -- The talks and consultations 
on the Black Sea Fleet which provoked a discord between Russia 
and Ukraine in the recent past, will need mutual concessions on 
both sides but should be held by all means in line with the 
agreement on the fleet which was signed by Boris Yeltsin and 
Leonid Kravchuk in Moscow on April 15, a high-ranking officer of 
the Russian Navy who refused to be identified, told ITAR-TASS on 
Tuesday. 
  On the other hand, he added, naval experts are apprehensive 
that the document opening the road to understandings on the 
Black Sea Fleet, can be doomed to the same fate as the Massandra 
Protocol singed by the two leaders last September, as well as 
earler understandings on this difficult problem. Incidentally, 
the protocol had clear benchmarks. 
  Experience showed that the adoption of documents does not 
mean real moves by the Ukrainian side to settle the fleet's 
problems. 
  Military sources in Moscow and Sevastopol report that 
pressure on Russian servicemen continues in Izmail and Ochakov 
even in the course of ten days which were given to draft an 
agreement on the division of the Black Sea Fleet, in order to 
force them to take the oath of allegience to Ukraine. Earlier, 
similar attempts were made in Odessa and Nikolayev. 
  Military experts believe that the Moscow agreement on the 
Black Sea Fleet has quite a number of "reefs". They note that, 
under the agreement, Sevastopol, the main base of the Black Sea 
Fleet, is not to have facilities of the Ukrainian Navy. 
  But it is highly improbable that Kiev will agree to this, 
although it understands that the two powerful administrative 
structures cannot rub elbows endlessly. 
  The cost of the Black Sea Fleet is another difficult problem 
to be tackled by Ukraine and Russia while settling the destiny 
of the fleet. One can count on serious progress in this sphere 
only after the fleet's assessment as well as the calculation of 
damage inflicted by Ukraine on Russia by "the lop-sided 
privatisation" of fleet ships (the figure reached 60 in two 
years' time). 
  Experts stress that the fate of the Black Sea Fleet can be 
sealed only on certain conditions which Ukraine should fulfill. 
For instance, it should not take lop-sided actions which will 
challenge the sincerety of the negotiating process. 
  That was the essence of the warning issued by the Russian 
president's press secretary Vyacheslav Kostikov on April 16 who 
said that the Ukrainian side, applying its usual "oozy" manner, 
started interpreting the understandings reached by the Russian 
and Ukrainian presidents in Moscow. 
  It began putting forth its own formulas concerning the 
lease, 
its periods and places of the fleet's deployment even before 
talks provided for by the agreement started. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16701 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov075_a_94027" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Offer To Repay Gas Debt `Unrealizable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine Offer To Repay Gas Debt `Unrealizable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1804145794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 16 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM1804145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sergey Leskov report: "As a Reward for Its Long-Suffering, </F>
`Gazprom' Hopes To Receive the Port of Odessa From Ukraine"] 
  [Text] Apart from everything else, the development of the 
conflict between "Gazprom" and Ukraine will make us delighted 
with the surgical genius who bound the economies of the 
fraternal republics together in such a way that it would be more 
correct to call them "Siamese twins." This conclusion can be 
drawn from the results of the Moscow talks between Ukrainian 
First Vice Premier Valentin Landyk and "Gazprom" Chairman Rem 
Vyakhirev. 
  They agreed that Ukraine's debt to the Russian gas industry 
is now $600 million, and that it will be paid off in the second 
quarter of 1994. However, you can read between the lines that 
neither of the sides is particularly relying on regular debt 
payments from Ukraine's empty budget pocket. For the first 
time, "Gazprom" did not threaten its neighbor with discontinuing 
supplies, and it did not mention the International Court. Gas 
is flowing through the pipeline, and will continue to flow. It 
is now obvious to everyone that it would primarily be Russia, 
which receives longed-for currency from the West for the export 
of gas, that would suffer from turning off the tap. 
  In this connection, the increasingly frequently mentioned 
possibility of "Gazprom" receiving property on the territory of 
Ukraine rather than money is acquiring particular significance. 
This time, apart from underground tanks and gas pipelines, 
Valentin Landyk has promised to give "Gazprom" a pretty fair 
part of the port of Odessa. The only thing that puts you on you 
guard is the simple fact that as the generosity of Kiev's 
proposals to the Russian gas industry increases, the clearer it 
becomes that these promises are unrealizable in practical terms. 
Foreign property on Ukraine's territory is not protected by 
legislation, and parliament has already had a sharply negative 
reaction to "Gazprom" having a share in a previous, narrower 
list of enterprises. As a result, the joint working group which 
is to coordinate the mechanism for turning the enterprises 
promised to "Gazprom" into joint-stock enterprises is getting 
practically nowhere in its activity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

