<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moldova Gas Supply Cut Off To Offset Debts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moldova Gas Supply Cut Off To Offset Debts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804132894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1026 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's joint stock company Gazprom cut gas supply 
to Moldova by one third because of that republic's debt totaling 
131 billion rubles by April 1, 1994. This was reported to 
Interfax by a well-placed Gazprom source. The company's current 
gas supply to Moldova amounts to 5.7 million cubic meters a day. 
  This year Moldova has not paid a single ruble to Gazprom, 
compensating for Russian gas partly in food supplies. 
  A Russo-Moldovan agreement signed at the end of 1993 commits 
Moldova to supplying to Gazprom $145 million worth in food 
stuffs and consumer goods in partial payment for the delivery of 
up to 3.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas. 
  Moldova now pays $80 for 1000 cubic meters of gas. To 
transport Russian gas across Moldova into Romania costs $1.5 per 
1000 cubic meters of gas over 100 kilometers of pipeline. 
  Meanwhile, the talks between a Belarusian Government 
delegation and Gazprom officials, scheduled for mid-April, have 
been put off indefinitely because of the signing of a monetary 
integration accord. During the negotiations the sides were to 
look over the fulfillment of a Russo-Belarusian protocol on 
paying off the debt for Russian gas. This accord was signed on 
March 15, 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

