<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Ossetia, Ingushetia To Continue Talks `In a Week' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Ossetia, Ingushetia To Continue Talks `In a Week' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804154694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] North Ossetia will cut short any attempt to wreck 
its current talks with Ingushetia, said an expert from the North 
Ossetian delegation to the negotiations between the two Russian 
Republics. In an interview with INTERFAX on Monday, he 
expressed the hope that the two sides would ultimately sign a 
final accord. "We wish to live in peace and intend to persuade 
the Ingush side to take the same position," he said. 
  North Ossetia believes it is impossible to stabilize the 
situation in the zone of the conflict between the two Republics 
unless Ingushetia gives up its claim to North Ossetia's 
Prigorodny District, the expert said. But he said none of the 
documents drawn up by the Ingush side had a provision to that 
effect. "In Kislovodsk, we agreed that we would not interfere 
into each other's internal affairs, but the Ingushes' claim to 
North Ossetian territory is precisely an instance of such 
interference," he said. 
  The expert said that, at the second round of talks, which 
ended on Friday, it had been suggested that North Ossetia's 
leadership get in direct contact with Ingush refugees wishing to 
return to Prigorodny District. "To date we only have 14,000 
applications from Ingushes, but, at the same time, we know that 
not all of the 40,000 wish to come back," he said. 
  According to some sources, the third round of talks is 
tentatively scheduled to start in a week. Meanwhile, experts on 
both sides will be working on the agreements, the sources told 
INTERFAX. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

