<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Antipoaching Operation on Far Eastern Frontier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Antipoaching Operation on Far Eastern Frontier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804121594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1138 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Borovkov] </F>
  [Text] Petropavlovsk-Kamchatskiy 18 April, TASS -- 
Commander-in-Chief of the Russian Frontier Guards Troops Andrey 
Nikolayev arrived in Kamchatka today. The main objectives of his 
visit are to get acquainted with the Far Eastern frontier guard 
districts and to start the putina (fishing season) operation. 
  The putina operation will begin in the Far East in the third 
decade of April. Its purpose is to stop the illegal fishing of 
Russian and foreign poachers in the economic zone of the Russian 
Federation. For half a year frontier guards jointly with the 
Fish Protection Service and the Navy will exercise a tough 
round-the-clock control over a vast part of the Pacific zone -- 
from the Chukotka Peninsula to the South Kuril islands. 
  Nikolayev said at the ramp of the plane that the operation 
would not affect the central part of the Sea of Okhotsk where 
Polish, Chinese and South Korean poacher vessels are illegally 
fishing the young fish, which are maturing there. "This is the 
problem of the national resources of the whole world and not 
only of Russia. It is necessary to resolve, in the first place, 
international problems connected with the use of biological 
resources of the Sea of Okhotsk," Nikolayev said. 
  Responding to the ITAR-TASS question about the reaction of 
Russia's Far Eastern neighbours to the putina operation, 
Nikolayev said that "all law-abiding states approve of those 
actions, aimed at protecting Russia's economic interests in the 
region." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

