<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views Federation Council Functions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Views Federation Council Functions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904111994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1024 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 19 TASS -- "It is already clear that 
the Council of the Federation cannot work on a non-permanent 
basis," Vladimir Shumeyko, speaker of the upper chamber of the 
Russian parliament, told a journalistic roundtable here today. 
"It will probably be necessary to amend the Constitution of the 
Russian Federation," he said, replying to an ITAR-TASS question 
on the organisation of the work of the parliament's upper 
chamber. In Shumeyko's opinion, members of the council should 
be elected and not delegated from each subject of the 
Federation. "It is impossible to combine the duties of a 
governor and senator," he noted. 
  Summing up the results of the first 100 days of the 
chamber's 
work, its speaker said that they were "spent on thinking over 
the functions of the upper chamber of the Federal Assembly". 
There are three points of view on this score among the MPs and 
in the society as a whole. The first view is that the council 
should work in strict accordance with the constitutional norms. 
The second view is that the chamber, being as it is the supreme 
legislative body, should tackle all the most important questions 
of social life, just as it was done by the old Supreme Soviet. 
This point of view is shared, in particular, by the heads of 
the subjects of the Federation, who account for the majority of 
the council members. And, finally, there is a view that the 
upper chamber should be "a buffer between the lower chamber and 
the president". This view is shared by the presidential 
administration. 
  Referring to the view of the heads of council committees, 
whom the speaker met on Monday, Shumeyko said that "the 
procedural rules of the Council of the Federation should be 
amended". The council must discuss all the vitally important 
problems, but at parliamentary hearings, not at sessions. Such 
hearings must be "an effective mechanism of its work". In some 
countries, the speaker recalled, they last for 1.5 years, 
discussing the most important problems and tabling proposals. 
Sessions of the chamber could be called whenever they are 
necessary, in particular, to endorse laws, presidential decrees, 
and other documents that are within the constitutional 
competence of the upper chamber. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16725 </DOCNO>
