<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commander Blames Abkhazia for Talks Deadlock </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commander Blames Abkhazia for Talks Deadlock </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804154594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The commander of Georgian Interior troops, Vladimir 
Chikovani, has accused Abkhazia of causing the impasse in the 
talks on the deployment of UN peacekeepers in the zone of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. The recent round of talks was held 
in Geneva. 
  In an interview with Interfax, Chikovani, who took part in 
the talks, said that the Abkhazian delegation occupied an 
"obstinate and unconstructive stand" and demanded the UN troops 
deployment along the confrontation line on the Inguri River. 
The Georgian troops, he said, are demanded by Abkhazia to be 
withdrawn eight kilometers away from the river. 
  Such demands, said Chikovani, run counter to commonsense and 
cannot guarantee the safety of refugees. 
  The Georgian side favors the deployment of peacekeepers 
along 
the entire territory of Abkhazia, including along the border 
with Russia which passes along the Psou River. 

</TEXT>

