<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Consults Parliamentary Groups on Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Consults Parliamentary Groups on Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804185694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1652 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 74 (564) for </F>
18 April 1994 compiled by Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy 
and edited by Vladimir Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Boris Yeltsin on Monday met Nikolay 
Medvedev, head of the parliamentary group of the New Regional 
Policy coalition. The meeting was held behind closed doors, but 
some sources told Interfax it had focused on the finalization of 
a draft for a civic accord, a proposed agreement between 
reformists and hardliners to prevent violence. The same subject 
was discussed at a meeting of a working group including the 
leaders of all eight parliamentary groups, also held on Monday. 
  Alevtina Fedulova, deputy chairwoman of the lower house of 
the legislature, said Yeltsin and the parliamentary group 
leaders were to consider the finalized draft of the accord at a 
meeting tentatively scheduled for April 22. But she said the 
meeting might be postponed if a draft taking account of all the 
suggestions and objections that had been made was not ready by 
that date. 
  IF Note: Some sources told Interfax some of the objections 
were very serious. For instance, the Communist group, headed by 
Gennadiy Zyuganov, protests against one of the fundamental 
points in the draft, a clause in which the signatories would 
pledge not to make any amendments to the Constitution that might 
destabilize the political situation in the country. Extreme 
nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovskiy said on Saturday that his 
Liberal Democratic Party would not sign the accord unless 
Yeltsin dismissed Anatoliy Chubays as deputy prime minister and 
chairman of the State Property Committee, Andrey Kozyrev as 
foreign minister and Viktor Yerin as interior minister. 

</TEXT>

