<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Seeks `Serious' NATO Partnership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Seeks `Serious' NATO Partnership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804180894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1705 
GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 18 Apr -- Russia's position regarding 
partnership with NATO has not changed, but the agreement to this 
effect should have real substance. A serious partnership 
requires closer political coordination, Andrey Kozyrev said to 
journalists today. 
  The relations of true partnership should rule out situations 
where important measures are being taken without consulting 
Russia in areas where close cooperation is needed -- as in, for 
example, looking for a solution to the Bosnia crisis, Kozyrev 
said. Moscow is interested in a serious agreement, stressed 
Kozyrev. 
  He also noted that all the sides involved will perhaps need 
some time to reflect on what it is that they want exactly. 
Russia intends to propose its own, really substantial draft 
agreement to NATO. We want a true, serious partnership, said 
the Russian foreign minister. 

</TEXT>

