<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Opposes Haste in Joining NATO's PFP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Opposes Haste in Joining NATO's PFP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904111294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1027 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- Russia "should not hasten to join 
NATO's Partnership for Peace [PFP] program," Federation Council 
Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko told reporters today. 
  The main thing in joining is "the reciprocity of partnership 
and a clear mechanism for implementing decisions," he said, 
stressing that the recent air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs, 
"when the decision was made not even by NATO but by the U.S. 
command, showed that a mechanism of this kind does not exist 
even at the level of the United Nations and the Security 
Council." 
  Shumeyko drew particular attention to the need for a 
mechanism "that will emphasize that all states in the 
partnership are absolutely equal." 
  "Further developments will show how the peace process will 
evolve," Vladimir Shumeyko said. 
  Under the Russian Constitution, it is the Federation Council 
that is responsible for the use of troops outside the country. 

</TEXT>

