<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Views Plan for CIS Integration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Views Plan for CIS Integration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904120194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1026 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 19 TASS -- A long-range plan of 
integration of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) is 
to be worked out by the Councils of Defence Ministers and of 
Foreign Ministers of the CIS by September 9, said Vladimir 
Shumeyko, chairman of Russia's Federation Council. The document 
being drafted on Boris Yeltsin's initiative is to determine how 
the Commonwealth develops in the areas of economy, policy and 
interstate relations, Shumeyko told reporters on Tuesday. 
  The head of the Interparliamentary Assembly of the CIS 
believes that the striving for closer economic cooperation was 
manifested at a meeting of heads of state of CIS countries in 
Moscow. He believes that the economic integration will lead to 
political integration and that the concept of the development of 
the CIS is important in this connection. Nazarbayev's proposal 
for the creation of a Eurasian union prompts this, Shumeyko said. 
  Shumeyko believes that changes in the CIS regulations will 
follow. Specifically, it should be stipulated that members of 
the CIS should not be in a state of war with each other. He 
said that Armenia and Azerbaijan are meant, above all. 
  Regarding the signing of the Russian-Belarussian 
[Belarusian] 
agreement on unifying the monetary systems, Shumeyko surmised 
that there will be no objections from the Federation Council to 
the ratification of the document. "It is necessary to visualise 
the ways of rapprochement of member-countries of the 
Commonwealth without infringing their sovereignty and freedoms," 
believes the speaker of the upper house of the Russian 
parliament. He said that the growing economic closeness of 
Russia and Belarus should only be encouraged as this has been 
the purpose of the entire previous economic policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

