<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomats, Soldiers Depart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomats, Soldiers Depart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804174494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A total of 100 servicemen from the Ukrainian 
military contingency of the UN peace-keeping battalion have left 
Kiev for ex-Yugoslavia. The Ukrainian Defense Ministry told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine that several diplomats, including the Ukrainian 
Foreign Ministry's Envoy, Andrey Ozadovskiy, had left for the 
conflict zone by the same plane. 
  The Ukrainian Foreign Ministry's press service said the 
Ukrainian diplomatic mission had left for ex-Yugoslavia in order 
to examine the situation in the region where the Ukrainian 
battalion was stationed and to conduct consultations on the 
issue. 
  The 550 men of the new contingency will be stationed near 
Gorazde. The Ukrainian servicemen were trained in the 
Prikarpatsky Military District. 
  The Ukrainian military contingency will be transported to 
ex-Yugoslavia by four flights. This will take three days. 
Ukraine is expected to have a 1,200-man military contingency in 
the region. The latest figure for the Ukrainian battalion in 
Bosnia and Herzegovina was 500 servicemen. 
  For the period of the Ukrainian battalion's presence in 
Sarajevo six servicemen have been killed and about 30 wounded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

